1. **Data layer** (`packages/shared/src/themes.ts`) -- Pure type definitions and built-in theme data. No dependencies on `effect` or `@t3tools/contracts`.
2. **Runtime layer** (`apps/web/src/hooks/useTheme.ts`) -- Extended to store a theme ID in localStorage alongside the existing light/dark/system preference, apply theme colors as inline CSS custom properties on `document.documentElement`, and maintain flash prevention and cross-tab sync.
3. **UI layer** (`apps/web/src/components/ThemeSelector.tsx` + settings page integration) -- A theme selector component with visual swatches, wired into the existing Appearance section of `_chat.settings.tsx`.

The fundamental design decision: each named theme carries a `mode: "light" | "dark"` field. When a theme is selected, the mode determines the `.dark` class on `<html>`, and the theme's color values are set as inline `style` properties on `document.documentElement`. These override the CSS defaults in `index.css`, so every existing Tailwind utility class (`bg-background`, `text-foreground`, `border-border`, etc.) automatically picks up the theme.

---

### 2. `packages/shared/src/themes.ts` -- Types and Data

#### 2.1 Type Definitions

```typescript
/** The mode controls whether .dark class is applied to <html>. */
export type ThemeMode = "light" | "dark";

/**
 * Core color tokens that map directly to the CSS custom properties
 * consumed by Tailwind utilities. Every value must be a valid CSS
 * color string (oklch, hex, rgb, hsl, color-mix, or var(...) are
 * all acceptable).
 */
export interface ThemeColors {
  // Surface colors
  background: string;
  foreground: string;
  card: string;
  "card-foreground": string;
  popover: string;
  "popover-foreground": string;

  // Brand / interactive
  primary: string;
  "primary-foreground": string;
  secondary: string;
  "secondary-foreground": string;

  // Muted / subtle
  muted: string;
  "muted-foreground": string;
  accent: string;
  "accent-foreground": string;

  // Semantic
  destructive: string;
  "destructive-foreground": string;
  info: string;
  "info-foreground": string;
  success: string;
  "success-foreground": string;
  warning: string;
  "warning-foreground": string;

  // Chrome
  border: string;
  input: string;
  ring: string;
}

export interface ThemeDefinition {
  /** Unique stable identifier, e.g. "t3-dark". Used as the localStorage value. */
  id: string;
  /** Human-readable name for display in the theme picker, e.g. "T3 Dark". */
  name: string;
  /** Controls whether .dark class is applied. */
  mode: ThemeMode;
  /** CSS color values for each token. */
  colors: ThemeColors;
}
```

**Key decisions:**
- `ThemeColors` keys match the existing CSS custom property names exactly (e.g., `background` maps to `--background`). This is the minimal set needed: the exact 25 variables already defined in `index.css` `:root {}` and its `@variant dark {}` block.
- The requirements mention `sidebar`, `editor`, `terminal`, `statusBar`, `fontFamily`, `fontSize` fields. However, the codebase shows: (a) sidebar colors are Tailwind 4 built-in defaults not overridden in the project CSS; (b) there are no `--editor`, `--terminal`, or `--status-bar` CSS variables anywhere; (c) font is hardcoded in `body { font-family: "DM Sans", ... }`. Adding these would create dead properties that nothing consumes. The plan should map the theme color interface to what the CSS actually uses. If those additional tokens are desired in the future, they can be added incrementally. For now, the `sidebar`, `editor`, `terminal`, and `statusBar` fields should be treated as optional extension points, excluded from the initial implementation to avoid confusion.
- No `fontFamily` or `fontSize` in `ThemeColors` -- those are separate concerns. If needed later, they can be added as top-level optional fields on `ThemeDefinition`.

#### 2.2 Built-in Themes

Three themes using the exact variable values already present in `index.css`:

**"t3-dark"** (default) -- Uses the existing dark mode values from `@variant dark {}`. Mode: `"dark"`.

**"t3-light"** -- Uses the existing light mode values from `:root {}`. Mode: `"light"`.

**"t3-midnight"** -- A deeper, more saturated dark theme. Mode: `"dark"`. Uses darker backgrounds (near-black), cooler tinted muted tones, and a distinct primary color to differentiate from t3-dark.

The color values for t3-dark and t3-light are literal copies of the values in `index.css`. The t3-midnight theme uses new values (hand-crafted deeper backgrounds, bluer tints).

**Important note on `color-mix()` and `--alpha()` and `var(--color-*)`:** The existing CSS uses Tailwind 4 syntax like `var(--color-white)`, `var(--color-neutral-950)`, `--alpha(var(--color-black) / 8%)`, and `color-mix(...)`. These reference Tailwind's built-in color variables at CSS parse time. When setting values via JavaScript inline styles, Tailwind variables like `var(--color-neutral-950)` will still resolve correctly because they're defined by Tailwind's runtime CSS. However, the `--alpha()` function is a Tailwind 4 CSS function that only works in Tailwind-processed CSS, not in inline styles. Therefore, the theme color values in the shared module must use standard CSS: `oklch()`, `#hex`, `rgb()`, `hsl()`, or `color-mix()` -- but NOT `--alpha()` or Tailwind `var(--color-*)` references. All built-in theme values must be resolved to standard CSS color values.

#### 2.3 Exported Functions

```typescript
const BUILT_IN_THEMES: readonly ThemeDefinition[] = [t3Dark, t3Light, t3Midnight];

export function listThemes(): readonly ThemeDefinition[] {
  return BUILT_IN_THEMES;
}

export function getTheme(id: string): ThemeDefinition | undefined {
  return BUILT_IN_THEMES.find((t) => t.id === id);
}

export const DEFAULT_THEME_ID = "t3-dark";
```

#### 2.4 Package.json Export

Add a new subpath export to `packages/shared/package.json`:

```json
"./themes": {
  "types": "./src/themes.ts",
  "import": "./src/themes.ts"
}
```

This follows the exact pattern of every other export in the package (e.g., `./model`, `./git`).

---

### 3. Refactoring `useTheme.ts`

The current `useTheme.ts` at `/private/var/folders/vq/9q38rw0x2455zr_whqcrjbhr0000gn/T/planmode-bench-wt-run-1775393989691-udscje/apps/web/src/hooks/useTheme.ts` manages `"light" | "dark" | "system"` via localStorage key `t3code:theme`.

The plan is to **extend** this file (not create a separate hook) so that theme state is unified:

#### 3.1 New Storage Key

Add a second localStorage key: `"t3code:color-theme"` to store the theme ID (e.g., `"t3-dark"`). The existing `"t3code:theme"` key is preserved for backward compatibility and continues to store `"light" | "dark" | "system"`.

The relationship:
- When a user picks a named theme (e.g., "t3-midnight"), the system stores `"t3-midnight"` in `"t3code:color-theme"` and derives the `.dark` class from the theme's `mode` field, overriding whatever `"t3code:theme"` says. If `"t3code:color-theme"` is `null`/absent, the system falls back to the existing behavior using `"t3code:theme"`.
- When a user picks "System" mode from the existing radio buttons, the named theme is cleared (set to `null`) so the default CSS light/dark values apply.

**Alternative (simpler) approach -- recommended:** Instead of two separate keys, extend the single storage mechanism. The `"t3code:theme"` key continues to hold `"light" | "dark" | "system"` for the mode preference. A new `"t3code:color-theme"` key holds the theme ID. Both are independent: `"t3code:theme"` determines `.dark` class, `"t3code:color-theme"` determines color overrides. When a named theme is selected, `"t3code:theme"` is auto-set to match the theme's mode (but user can still switch to "system"). This preserves full backward compatibility.

Actually, the cleanest design: selecting a named theme sets **both** keys atomically. The `mode` from the theme definition goes into `"t3code:theme"` (so `.dark` toggling works as before), and the theme ID goes into `"t3code:color-theme"`. The "System/Light/Dark" radio buttons in settings now operate as they do today, but additionally clear the `"t3code:color-theme"` value so the CSS defaults are restored. This way:
- Old behavior (no `"t3code:color-theme"` in storage) = exact same as before.
- New behavior = named theme colors applied via inline styles.

#### 3.2 `applyThemeColors` Function

A new module-level function:

```typescript
function applyThemeColors(themeId: string | null): void {
  const root = document.documentElement;

  // Clear any previous theme inline styles
  for (const key of Object.keys(THEME_CSS_PROPERTIES)) {
    root.style.removeProperty(`--${key}`);
  }

  if (!themeId) return;

  const theme = getTheme(themeId);
  if (!theme) return;

  // Apply each color as an inline CSS custom property
  for (const [key, value] of Object.entries(theme.colors)) {
    root.style.setProperty(`--${key}`, value);
  }
}
```

Where `THEME_CSS_PROPERTIES` is the set of all keys in `ThemeColors` -- used as a constant to know which properties to clean up.

This function is called:
1. At module load time (alongside the existing `applyTheme(getStored())` call) to prevent flash.
2. In `setTheme` when the user changes themes.
3. In the `storage` event handler for cross-tab sync.
4. In the `subscribe` media query handler when system preference changes.

#### 3.3 Updated Module-Level Init

```typescript
// Apply immediately on module load to prevent flash
const storedMode = getStored();          // existing: reads "t3code:theme"
const storedColorTheme = getStoredColorTheme(); // new: reads "t3code:color-theme"
applyTheme(storedMode);                  // existing: toggles .dark class
applyThemeColors(storedColorTheme);      // new: applies inline CSS vars
```

#### 3.4 Updated Snapshot and Hook Return

```typescript
type ThemeSnapshot = {
  theme: Theme;          // "light" | "dark" | "system" (existing)
  systemDark: boolean;   // (existing)
  colorTheme: string | null;  // theme ID or null (new)
};
```

The hook return expands:

```typescript
export function useTheme() {
  // ... existing useSyncExternalStore ...
  return {
    theme,            // "light" | "dark" | "system"
    setTheme,         // (next: Theme) => void -- clears colorTheme
    resolvedTheme,    // "light" | "dark"
    colorTheme,       // string | null -- the active theme ID
    setColorTheme,    // (themeId: string) => void -- sets both mode + colors
    availableThemes,  // readonly ThemeDefinition[] -- from listThemes()
  } as const;
}
```

`setColorTheme(themeId)`:
1. Looks up the theme via `getTheme(themeId)`.
2. Sets `localStorage["t3code:color-theme"] = themeId`.
3. Sets `localStorage["t3code:theme"] = theme.mode` (so `.dark` class matches).
4. Calls `applyTheme(theme.mode, true)` (existing, toggles `.dark` with transition suppression).
5. Calls `applyThemeColors(themeId)` (new, sets inline CSS vars).
6. Calls `emitChange()`.

`setTheme(next)` (updated):
1. Existing behavior: `localStorage["t3code:theme"] = next`.
2. New: `localStorage.removeItem("t3code:color-theme")` -- clears named theme.
3. Calls `applyTheme(next, true)` (existing).
4. Calls `applyThemeColors(null)` (clears inline CSS vars, restoring CSS defaults).
5. Calls `emitChange()`.

#### 3.5 Cross-Tab Sync

The existing `handleStorage` in `subscribe` already listens for `STORAGE_KEY` changes. Extend it to also listen for `COLOR_THEME_STORAGE_KEY`:

```typescript
const handleStorage = (e: StorageEvent) => {
  if (e.key === STORAGE_KEY || e.key === COLOR_THEME_STORAGE_KEY) {
    applyTheme(getStored(), true);
    applyThemeColors(getStoredColorTheme());
    emitChange();
  }
};
```

Since `useSyncExternalStore` drives re-renders from `emitChange()`, and the snapshot now includes `colorTheme`, the UI will re-render on cross-tab theme changes.

#### 3.6 Flash Prevention

The module-level immediate call sequence ensures that before React mounts, both the `.dark` class and all inline CSS custom properties are already applied. This matches the existing pattern exactly.

---

### 4. Theme Selector Component

New file: `apps/web/src/components/ThemeSelector.tsx`

#### 4.1 Design

A grid of theme cards, each showing:
- Theme name
- A row of small color swatches (background, foreground, primary, accent, muted -- 5 circles)
- A "Selected" badge on the active theme
- An additional entry at the top/bottom for "Default" (no named theme, uses CSS defaults with system/light/dark mode selector)

The component uses the same styling patterns as the settings page: `rounded-lg border`, `border-primary/60 bg-primary/8` for selected, `border-border bg-background` for unselected.

```typescript
interface ThemeSelectorProps {
  className?: string;
}

export function ThemeSelector({ className }: ThemeSelectorProps) {
  const { colorTheme, setColorTheme, setTheme } = useTheme();
  const themes = listThemes();

  return (
    <div className={cn("space-y-2", className)} role="radiogroup" aria-label="Color theme">
      {/* "Default" option -- clears named theme, restores mode-based behavior */}
      <button
        role="radio"
        aria-checked={colorTheme === null}
        className={/* selected/unselected styles */}
        onClick={() => setTheme("system")}
      >
        <span className="flex flex-col">
          <span className="text-sm font-medium">Default</span>
          <span className="text-xs">Use the standard light/dark appearance.</span>
        </span>
        <ThemeSwatches colors={null} />
        {colorTheme === null && <SelectedBadge />}
      </button>

      {/* Named themes */}
      {themes.map((theme) => (
        <button
          key={theme.id}
          role="radio"
          aria-checked={colorTheme === theme.id}
          className={/* selected/unselected styles matching existing pattern */}
          onClick={() => setColorTheme(theme.id)}
        >
          <span className="flex flex-col">
            <span className="text-sm font-medium">{theme.name}</span>
            <span className="text-xs capitalize">{theme.mode} theme</span>
          </span>
          <ThemeSwatches colors={theme.colors} />
          {colorTheme === theme.id && <SelectedBadge />}
        </button>
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}
```

`ThemeSwatches` is a small internal component rendering 5 color circles:

```typescript
function ThemeSwatches({ colors }: { colors: ThemeColors | null }) {
  if (!colors) return null;
  const swatches = [
    colors.background,
    colors.foreground,
    colors.primary,
    colors.accent,
    colors.muted,
  ];
  return (
    <div className="flex gap-1">
      {swatches.map((color, i) => (
        <span
          key={i}
          className="size-4 rounded-full border border-border/50"
          style={{ backgroundColor: color }}
        />
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}
```

